 3.2 Field and sigma-field Definition 2.1 (Field) The class \(\mathcal{A}\) of subsets of \(\Omega\) is called a field if it contains \(\Omega\) and is closed under the formation of complements and finite unions, that is if: \(\Omega \in \mathcal{A}\); \(A \in \mathcal{A} \Rightarrow A^c \in \mathcal{A}\); \(A_{1}, A_{2}\in\mathcal{A} \Rightarrow A_{1} \cup A_{2} \in \mathcal{A}\). Proposition 2.1 (Definition of a field) The condition 3 of the definition of a field can be replaced by \(A_{1}, A_{2} \in \mathcal{A} \Rightarrow A_{1} \cap A_{2} \in \mathcal{A}\). That means, \(\mathcal{A}\) is closed under finite intersections. Proof. By de Morgan laws, \((A_{1} \cap A_{2})^{C} = A_{1}^{C} \cup A_{2}^{C}\) and \((A_{1} \cup A_{2})^{c} = A_{1}^{C} \cap A_{2}^{C}\). By the condition 2 of the definition of a field, we can get the desired result. Exercise 2.1 Which of the followings are \(\sigma\)-fields of subsets of \(\Omega=\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}?\) \(\{ \{1,2,\}, \{1,2,3,\}, \{4,5,6\}, \emptyset, \Omega \}\). \(\{ \{1,2\}, \{3,4,5,6\}, \emptyset, \Omega \}\). \(\{ \{1\}, \{3,4,5,6\}, \{1,3,4,5,6\},\Omega \}\). Solution. b. Definition 2.2 (Semi-field) Let \(\Omega\) be an arbitrary set. A non-empty class \(\mathcal{J}\) of subsets of \(\Omega\) is called a semi-field if \(\Omega = \mathcal{J}, \emptyset \in \mathcal{J}\), \(\mathcal{J}\) is closed under the formation of finite intersections, and the complement of any set in \(\mathcal{J}\) is a finite sum of disjoint sets of \(\mathcal{J}\). It is easy to see that any field of subsets of \(\Omega\) is also a semi-field. However, the following simple examples show that the converse is not true. Example 2.2 (A class of events which is a semi-field but not a field) 1. Let \(\Omega=[-\infty, \infty)\) and \(\mathcal{J}_{1}\), contain \(\Omega\), \(\{\infty\}\) and all intervals of the type \([a,b)\) where \(-\infty &lt; a \leq b \leq \infty\). Then, \(\emptyset \in \mathcal{J}_{1}\), \(\Omega \in \mathcal{J}_{1}\), \([a_{1}, b_{1}) \cap [a_{2}, b_{2})=[a_{1} \vee a_{2}, b_{1} \wedge b_{2})\in\mathcal{J}_{1}\), and \([a,b)^{C}=[-\infty, a)\cup[b, \infty)\). So, \(\mathcal{J}_{1}\), is a semi-field. Obviously \(\mathcal{J}_{1}\) is not a field (Check 2.3). Take \(\Omega = \mathbb{R}^{1}\) and denote by \(\mathcal{J}_{2}\) the class of all subsets of the form \(A\cap B\) where \(A\) is closed and \(B\) is an open set in \(\Omega\). Then again, \(\mathcal{J}_{2}\) is a semi-field but not a field. Definition 2.3 (Sigma-field) The class \(\mathcal{F}\) of subsets of \(\Omega\) is called a \(\sigma\)-field if it is a field and closed under the formation of countable unions, that is if: \(A_{1}, A_{2}, \ldots, \in \mathcal{F} \Rightarrow  igcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n} \in \mathcal{F}\). Proposition 2.2 (Definition of a sigma-field) The condition 4 of the definition of a sigma-field can be replaced by \(A_{1}, A_{2}, \ldots, \in \mathcal{F} \Rightarrow  igcap_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n} \in \mathcal{F}\). That means, \(\sigma\)-field \(\mathcal{F}\) is closed under countable intersections because \( igcap_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n} = ( igcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}^{C})^{C}\) and each \(A_{n}^{C}\) belongs to \(\mathcal{F}\). Proof. By de Morgan lawsand condition 2 of the definition of a field, \(( igcap_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n})^{C}= igcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}^{C}\in\mathcal{F}\) and \(( igcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n})^{C}= igcap_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}^{C}\in\mathcal{F}\). So, we can change the condition 4. Usually, \(\mathcal{F}\) is the set of events (subsets of \(\Omega\)) we are allowed to consider. Definition 2.4 (Random events (events)) The elements of any field of \(\sigma\)-field are called random events (or simply, events). Example 2.3 (A class of events which is a field but not a sigma-field) Let \(\Omega = [0, \infty)\) and \(\mathcal{F}_{1}\) be the class of all intervals of the type \([a,b)\) or \([a,\infty)\), where \(0 \leq a &lt; b &lt; \infty\). Let \(\mathcal{F}_{2}\) be the class of all finite sums of intervals of \